    <h1>Static, Readonly, and Const in C#</h1>
    <p>In C#, <strong>static</strong>, <strong>readonly</strong>, and <strong>const</strong> are used to define values and members with specific behaviors:</p>

    <h2>1. Static</h2>
    <p>A <strong>static</strong> member belongs to the class rather than an instance. You can access it without creating an object.</p>
    <div class="code-container">
        <div class="code-header">Example: Static Member</div>
        <div class="code-content">
<pre><code class="language-csharp">
public class Calculator
{
    public static double Pi = 3.14159;
}

Console.WriteLine(Calculator.Pi); // Output: 3.14159
</code></pre>
        </div>
    </div>

    <h2>2. Readonly</h2>
    <p>A <strong>readonly</strong> field can only be assigned during declaration or in a constructor. It cannot be modified elsewhere.</p>
    <div class="code-container">
        <div class="code-header">Example: Readonly Field</div>
        <div class="code-content">
<pre><code class="language-csharp">
public class Circle
{
    public readonly double Radius;

    public Circle(double radius)
    {
        Radius = radius;
    }
}

Circle c = new Circle(5);
// c.Radius = 10; // Error: Cannot assign to readonly field
</code></pre>
        </div>
    </div>

    <h2>3. Const</h2>
    <p>A <strong>const</strong> field is a compile-time constant and must be assigned during declaration. It cannot be changed later.</p>
    <div class="code-container">
        <div class="code-header">Example: Const Field</div>
        <div class="code-content">
<pre><code class="language-csharp">
public class MathConstants
{
    public const double Gravity = 9.81;
}

Console.WriteLine(MathConstants.Gravity); // Output: 9.81
</code></pre>
        </div>
    </div>

    <h2>Key Points</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Static:</strong> Shared by all instances of a class.</li>
        <li><strong>Readonly:</strong> Set at runtime but only once per instance.</li>
        <li><strong>Const:</strong> Set at compile-time and cannot change.</li>
        <li>Use static for shared utilities, readonly for values that are initialized once, and const for fixed constants.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Exercise</h2>
    <p>Create a class <code>Earth</code> with:</p>
    <ul>
        <li>a <strong>const</strong> field <code>Radius</code> = 6371</li>
        <li>a <strong>readonly</strong> field <code>CreationYear</code> set via constructor</li>
        <li>a <strong>static</strong> field <code>PlanetCount</code> incremented each time an <code>Earth</code> object is created</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Test your class by creating multiple objects and printing all fields.</p>

